#SSL/TLS Protocol
SSL (Secure Socket Layer) and TLS (Transport Layer Security) are cryptographic protocols used to secure communication over the internet.
TLS is the modern and more secure version of SSL.
These protocols create a secure, encrypted pathway between the client and server over the internet.
Ensuring data transmitted across the internet remains confidential, authentic, and protected from tampering.
One common example is HTTPS. In HTTPS, the standard HTTP protocol is secured using SSL/TLS encryption. The "s" in HTTPS stands for
secure, indicating that the connection is protected using digital certificates and encryption provided by SSL/TLS.
Digital certificates are issued by trusted Certificate Authorities (CAs) and are used to verify the identity of websites. This helps
prevent attackers from impersonating legitimate servers.
SSL/TLS is not limited to securing websites. It can also be used in other applications, such as SSL VPNs, where a client remotely
and securely connects to a corporate network through a firewall. This allows authorized users to access internal resources like files,
databases, and applications remotely while maintaining secure, encrypted communications.
Many VPN providers use similar encryption technologies to protect data while accessing the internet.
